 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.9.2","title":"robot-redesign/validation: add SQLite, adapter, degraded-source, and restart-recovery integration tests","description":"Add integration coverage for the runtime projection store, adapter normalization, degraded-source handling, attention replay, watermark persistence, incident evolution, and restart recovery behavior. This task exists because the hardest parts of the redesign live at the seams between subsystems, not inside isolated helper functions.","design":"The tests should exercise realistic sequences such as source outage followed by partial recovery, ntm restart followed by resumed delta computation, incident promotion after repeated evidence, projection rebuild with durable cursor continuity, ambiguous timeout followed by safe retry, duplicate request suppression with later verified outcome, repeated flapping source with cooldown and resurfacing, acknowledgment followed by material change and resurfacing, snooze expiry, pin and manual escalation behavior, retention or pruning decisions, and partial transport resync. They should use the shared deterministic harness and log scenario IDs, request IDs, idempotency keys, cursor transitions, watermark state, source_health changes, operator-state transitions, suppression or resurfacing markers, incident fingerprints, and assertion diffs with enough detail to diagnose failures quickly. This task should prove the redesign works as an operational system, not just as a collection of structs.","acceptance_criteria":"This task is complete when the critical persistence, degradation, replay, restart-safety, retry-safety, attention-hygiene, and operator-control promises of the redesign are pinned by deterministic integration tests that emit rich debugging context and fail loudly when those promises regress.","notes":"Future self: if you ever want to simplify something 'just for now,' make sure these tests still express the product promises that matter.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type