 {"id":"bd-j9jo3.9.3","title":"robot-redesign/validation: add end-to-end operator-loop and parity coverage","description":"Add Go-based end-to-end coverage for the operator loop across CLI and server transports. This task exists because the redesign is fundamentally about making ntm easier to operate over time, and that must be validated at the product-behavior level with reproducible test drivers, not only with lower-level tests.","design":"The E2E suite should live under e2e/ and exercise bootstrap via snapshot, tending via digest and attention, explainability via diagnostic drill-down, drill-down via inspect surfaces, and parity across CLI, REST, and streaming where appropriate. It should cover happy-path, degraded-source, replay or resync, invalid cursor, invalid inspect target, restart-recovery, incident-heavy, bounded-output, safe-retry, duplicate-request, aggregated-attention, cooldown, resurfacing, operator acknowledgment, snooze, pin, manual escalation, and why-is-this-like-this scenarios using Go-based drivers and checked-in testdata rather than ad hoc shell scripts. The suite should log commands, HTTP requests, request IDs, idempotency keys, cursors, schema IDs, payload sizes, truncation or pagination activation, operator-state transitions, suppression or resurfacing markers, error codes, remediation hints, diagnostic handles, evidence summaries, changed sections, key excerpts from responses, and assertion diffs in enough detail that a failed run tells future implementers exactly what regressed.","acceptance_criteria":"This task is complete when go test -v ./e2e/... exercises the intended operator loop and transport parity with deterministic scenarios and great detailed logging, including safe retries, correlated outcomes, compact attention behavior, and durable operator control, and when failures surface enough context to debug behavior without rerunning blindly.","notes":"E2E coverage should validate the product story, not merely prove that a few endpoi